project.title: Scene Chunks Tutorial
project.logline: A screenplay that teaches you how to use Scene Chunks by letting the app itself guide you through the features.

chunk_intro.title: INT. SCENE CHUNKS HQ - DAY

body.text: A glowing cursor blinks on the screen. The SCENE CHUNKS LOGO flickers to life like an old CRT monitor.

body.dialogue: Welcome to Scene Chunks! Think of me as your co-writer who never complains about rewrites.
Finally, a partner who doesn’t steal all the credit.
I’ll walk you through the features — scene by scene — so you’ll be chunking brilliance in no time.

chunk_intro.notes: Opening image: introduce the interface and meta tone.

chunk_structure.title: INT. WRITER’S ROOM - LATER

body.dialogue: See that sidebar on the left? Each of those boxes is a scene chunk. You can drag them to reorder your story.
You can also lock scenes to structure beats — Opening Image, Midpoint, Finale — and I’ll keep them right where they belong.
Like an obedient story robot.
Exactly! Down below, there’s a colorful structure bar showing your film’s flow. When you fill scenes in, it glows like progress in a video game.

chunk_structure.notes: Describes structure visualization and locked beats.

body.dialogue: Let’s talk dialogue. Every block you type here is formatted like a proper screenplay — centered names, dialogue below, and optional parentheticals.

body.text: a FLYING SAUCER flies across the screen.

body.dialogue: So I just hit Tab for a new action, and Shift+Tab for a new dialogue block?
Exactly! You’re a natural already. You can even duplicate, copy, or delete blocks with those icons on the right.

body.text: A sparkle animation plays above Nate’s head. It’s very satisfying.

body.dialogue: Sometimes two characters speak at once — that’s where dual dialogue comes in!

left.dialogue: Wow, this really looks like Final Draft!

body.dialogue: Dual dialogue prints correctly in the preview and export. Two voices, one moment of cinematic chaos.
Highlight any word in your action text — say, a GUN or a DOOR — and tag it as a PROP or CHARACTER.
That text will turn uppercase and appear in your chunk’s prop list. You can even view a global prop list or highlight all props on screen!
Effortlessly track continuity and inventory. You’ll thank me when you’re on set.

chunk_characters.title: EXT. CHARACTER PANEL - AFTERNOON

body.dialogue: Now let’s check out the Character Panel. Click the character icon on the sidebar — see it?
It shows every character in your story, what scenes they appear in, and even their total line count!
That’s actually really useful for balancing screen time.
Exactly. No more forgetting that one side character who vanished after Act 1.
You can also add or edit characters here directly — everything stays synced with your scenes.

chunk_characters.notes: Introduces the Character Panel and its uses.

body.dialogue: That’s everything! You can preview, export, and print your masterpiece in proper screenplay format.
Now go forth, writer. Chunk boldly. Rewrite endlessly.
You’re gonna make me cry digital tears.
